The Vice President of the United States, Mike Pence, delivered remarks at the Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the Apollo 11 mission. He unveiled the spacesuit worn by Neil Armstrong during his historic moonwalk and highlighted the risks and challenges faced by the astronauts during their journey to the moon. Pence praised Armstrong's courage and professionalism, noting his calmness and quick thinking during the lunar module landing. He also expressed gratitude to the Apollo astronauts and the American people for their contributions to space exploration. Pence emphasized the importance of preserving these artifacts as symbols of courage and inspiration for future generations. He mentioned President Trump's commitment to American leadership in space and the goal of returning to the moon within the next five years. Pence concluded by honoring the memory and legacy of Neil Armstrong and expressing hope that the spacesuit would inspire future heroes.